2026-04-21 01:40:05 | INFO     | DiagnosticAssistantLLM | OUTPUT: suggestion_type='hypothesis' action_type=None action_target=None action_description=None suspected_components=['ambient light sensor device in control module'] hypothesis_explanation='The power module is stable at ~11.85 V and correctly polarized, the relay coil and contacts are reported healthy, and sweeping the timing potentiometer over its full range does not change the ~20 s on–off cycling of the lamp. The supply and bias network voltages are normal (about 11.85 V supply with ~5.9 V across the light sensor), so the driver and reference rails are not undervoltage. Yet the simulator flags the control path as in an unstable or oscillating state, and varying the external illumination from very dark to very bright does not cleanly switch and latch the output but leaves the system in a recurrent oscillation.\n\nWith stable DC rails and intact relay hardware, the remaining likely cause of autonomous periodic switching is an internal fault of the light-sensing element itself (e.g., partial intermittent conduction, leakage or noise causing the comparator/driver to cross its threshold periodically) rather than of the passive bias components or potentiometers, which test as normal. Therefore the root cause is most probably a faulty ambient light sensor device in the control module, and it should be replaced or repaired.'
