2026-04-21 01:40:19 | INFO     | DiagnosticAssistantLLM | OUTPUT: suggestion_type='hypothesis' action_type=None action_target=None action_description=None suspected_components=['relay driver / comparator IC in control module', 'hysteresis / feedback network components for relay driver in control module (e.g., feedback resistor, associated capacitor or wiring)'] hypothesis_explanation='The supply rails, light sensor, and its bias network all show stable DC levels around 11.85 V and ~5.9 V, so the periodic ~20 s dropout of the lamp is not coming from the sensor itself or from a missing/unstable supply. Tests varying ambient light and sweeping the timing potentiometer do not remove the ~20 s cycling; the relay remains closed and the lamp lit, but the simulation consistently flags an unstable or oscillating state at the relay driver output node. The sensor node is stable while the relay driver/output node is not, which localizes the fault to the driver / hysteresis network that converts the sensor voltage into a clean relay control. A failure of the comparator/driver IC or of its feedback (hysteresis/timing) network components or their interconnections can produce slow autonomous oscillation even with constant sensor input, matching the observed periodic off‑intervals. Therefore the most likely root cause is a fault in the relay driver/comparator stage or its feedback network, not in the sensor or power modules.'
