2026-04-21 01:40:48 | INFO     | DiagnosticAssistantLLM | OUTPUT: suggestion_type='hypothesis' action_type=None action_target=None action_description=None suspected_components=['main lamp (load bulb) in load module', 'lamp socket / internal series connections within load module', 'series diode in load module', 'internal wiring to small indicator lamp in load module'] hypothesis_explanation='The control and supply modules show stable DC voltages: the battery is fine, the control module rails and sensor bias are steady, the relay coil terminals both sit at ~11.85 V (so the relay is not actually switching), and the load module input terminals remain at a steady ~11.8 V / 0 V while the observed flicker occurs. The main lamp itself measures about 11 V across it during testing, i.e. it is continuously energized even when it visually goes dark. This rules out upstream intermittent drive or polarity issues and points to an internal problem local to the load module.\n\nGiven a constant applied voltage yet periodic extinguishing with roughly a 20 s period, the only plausible mechanism is an internal, thermally or mechanically intermittent fault in the lamp or its immediate series path: e.g. a filament that is fractured and making intermittent contact, a poor connection in the lamp socket, or an intermittent failure of the series diode or internal wiring common to both lamps. As the component heats, the connection opens briefly (lamp goes out), cools, and remakes contact, leading to cyclic behavior independent of the control circuitry.\n\nTherefore the root cause is best explained by a faulty main lamp or its immediate internal series path in the load module (including the series diode or socket/wiring). Replacing/repairing these load‑module components should eliminate the periodic 20 s off‑on cycling while the module continues to receive steady DC from the control module.'
