2026-04-21 01:41:32 | INFO     | DiagnosticAssistantLLM | OUTPUT: suggestion_type='hypothesis' action_type=None action_target=None action_description=None suspected_components=['timing potentiometer in control (ambient sensor) module', 'sensitivity potentiometer in control (ambient sensor) module', 'associated potentiometer modeling/parameter configuration causing simulation instability'] hypothesis_explanation='All power‑path hardware behaves nominally: the battery, power LED, relay coil and contacts, control‑module output, load‑module input, series diode, main lamp and indicator lamp all show correct voltages and no observable faults. The relay coil never actually sees a changing drive; both ends remain at the same potential, and the control‑module output to the load is a steady ~11.85 V referenced to ~0 V. Direct visual observation confirms both lamps remain steadily lit, with no real 20‑s extinguishing. The only persistent anomaly is the simulator’s report of a ‘non‑converging, unstable or oscillating’ state tied to the control relay/driver node whenever the timing potentiometer is swept. Yet attempts to test continuity on the timing and sensitivity potentiometers fail because these components have no defined resistance parameter in the diagnostic environment. This strongly indicates that the potentiometers (or their model/parameters) are mis‑specified in the circuit definition: e.g., missing or zero/undefined resistance values or wiper behaviour that leaves the driver input in an indeterminate numerical state. That modelling/configuration defect can create a slow numerical oscillation in the simulated driver node, which is then interpreted as a 20‑s flicker, even though electrically the lamp branch is continuously powered. Therefore the root cause is a configuration/modelling fault associated with the timing and/or sensitivity potentiometers, rather than any physical component failure in the power, control, or load circuitry.'
