2026-04-21 01:42:27 | INFO     | DiagnosticAssistantLLM | OUTPUT: suggestion_type='hypothesis' action_type=None action_target=None action_description=None suspected_components=['ground / reference node interconnections between modules (negative cables and their terminations)'] hypothesis_explanation='Diagnostics show that all functional components behave nominally (battery, LEDs, sensor, relay, lamps, potentiometers, wiring, diode, and contacts), and that the control and load modules both receive a stable ~11.8 V supply with correct polarity. The relay contacts are not actually interrupting power, and both lamps remain visibly steady. However, the latest continuity/voltage test on the 0 V reference reveals that the negative rails of the power‑supply, control, and load modules are not at a single common potential: there are small but finite offsets (up to ~45.7 mV) between the various negative cables instead of one unified ground node. This implies that the modules’ grounds are not properly tied together (e.g., missing or mis‑connected ground/return links, separate reference nets that should be shorted, or an open/incorrect ground jumper). In a circuit simulator this can manifest as an ‘unstable or oscillating’ or non‑converging operating point, because the solver sees multiple quasi‑floating reference nodes. Logically, this is the only remaining systemic inconsistency after ruling out individual components and polarity errors. Therefore, the root cause is a configuration/wiring fault in the ground/reference node interconnections between modules; repairing these (ensuring all negative cables and internal ground symbols are truly bonded into a single 0 V net) should eliminate the reported instability/flicker without needing to replace any active components.'
