description: Probe the relay driver stage to see whether it is oscillating autonomously: using measure_voltage, monitor over time the voltage at the comparator output that drives the relay coil, as well as the node providing feedback/hysteresis to its input (if exposed) while the ambient light is held constant. Determine whether this node, rather than the sensor, is periodically ramping or toggling, indicating a fault in the driver or its feedback network., outcome='The relay driver/output node is unstable or oscillating, as indicated by the non‑converging simulation at the control relay (both terminals near 11.85 V). The sensor bias resistor shows a stable drop from about 11.85 V to 5.94 V, suggesting its node is not exhibiting the same instability.\nCurrent persistent circuit state [differences with the starting state]:\nNo circuit-level changes introduced by diagnostics.', precise_action_cost=45.0, cost_breakdown=[('open_inspection_panel', 5.0), ('measure_voltage', 20.0), ('measure_voltage', 20.0)], simplified_outcome=None), DiagnosticActionResult(action=
name: Observe -> control (ambient sensor) module potentiometer wiring and PCB traces,
description: Visually inspect the timing and sensitivity potentiometers and their PCB connections (including any tracks or jumpers from the wipers to the relay driver circuit) for mis‑wiring, missing/unsoldered wiper connection, or unintended shorts that could leave the relay driver input floating and cause oscillation., outcome='The timing and sensitivity potentiometers both show no observable internal faults; their wiper positions are at 1.0 (timing) and 0.5 (sensitivity). The control panel is open, and the control relay appears visually normal and is currently closed.\nCurrent persistent circuit state [differences with the starting state]:\nNo circuit-level changes introduced by diagnostics.', precise_action_cost=35.0, cost_breakdown=[('observe_component', 10.0), ('observe_component', 10.0), ('open_inspection_panel', 5.0), ('observe_component', 10.0)], simplified_outcome=None), DiagnosticActionResult(action=
name: Test -> control module relay coil and its drive path to supply/ground,
description: Measure the DC voltage at each side of the control relay coil with respect to the control module reference while the lamp is exhibiting the ~20 s flicker, to verify whether the coil is truly being driven between supply and ground or if both ends remain near the same potential (indicating that the apparent relay-state oscillation is an artifact and the true oscillation is occurring elsewhere, e.g., in the load module)., outcome='The relay coil’s positive and negative terminals both measure approximately 11.85 V relative to the control module reference during the flicker, indicating that the two coil ends remain at nearly the same potential. No polarity inversion between coil terminals is indicated by these measurements.\nCurrent persistent circuit state [differences with the starting state]:\nNo circuit-level changes introduced by diagnostics.', precise_action_cost=25.0, cost_breakdown=[('open_inspection_panel', 5.0), ('measure_voltage', 20.0)], simplified_outcome=None), DiagnosticActionResult(action=
name: Test -> load module (lamp circuit including series diode and small indicator lamp),
description: Use a measure_voltage diagnostic across the two input terminals of the load module, and across the main lamp itself, during the ~20 s flicker event. Confirm whether the load module sees a steady DC input from the control module while the main lamp briefly extinguishes, and whether the voltage across the lamp actually drops to near 0 V or remains near the supply value when the light goes out., outcome='The load module input terminals see a steady DC-like input of about 11.8 V on (+) relative to ground and near 0 V on (−), despite the reported instability warning. The main lamp voltage is about 11.0 V from its positive side to the same near‑ground negative reference, indicating the lamp is actually seeing close to the supply voltage during the measurement interval.\nCurrent persistent circuit state [differences with the starting state]:\nNo circuit-level changes introduced by diagnostics.', precise_action_cost=60.0, cost_breakdown=[('measure_voltage', 20.0), ('measure_voltage', 20.0), ('measure_voltage', 20.0)], simplified_outcome=None), DiagnosticActionResult(action=
name: Test -> physical lamp output and environment (human‑eye observation vs. circuit state),
description: Use an observe_output or equivalent diagnostic to monitor whether the main lamp is actually turning off every ~20 s, or whether the perceived flicker is an artefact of the simulation/measurement (e.g., sampling or convergence issue). Compare direct visual observation of lamp brightness over several cycles with the logged circuit node voltages to determine if any real change in light output occurs., outcome='The requested action could not be mapped to any recognized diagnostic operation. Only actions from the available action list are supported (e.g. measure_voltage, test_continuity, inspect_connections, verify_repair, …).\nCurrent persistent circuit state [differences with the starting state]:\nNo circuit-level changes introduced by diagnostics.', precise_action_cost=0.0, cost_breakdown=[], simplified_outcome=None), DiagnosticActionResult(action=
name: Test -> main lamp light output vs. electrical state in load module,
description: Use an observe_output or equivalent supported diagnostic (e.g., verify_repair/measure_photo-sensor if available) to directly determine whether the main lamp’s luminous output actually drops every ~20 s or whether the perceived flicker is only a simulation artefact, while simultaneously logging the voltage across the lamp to correlate light output with electrical conditions., outcome='The requested action could not be mapped to any recognized diagnostic operation. Only actions from the available action list are supported (e.g. measure_voltage, test_continuity, inspect_connections, verify_repair, …).\nCurrent persistent circuit state [differences with the starting state]:\nNo circuit-level changes introduced by diagnostics.', precise_action_cost=0.0, cost_breakdown=[], simplified_outcome=None), DiagnosticActionResult(action=
name: Observe -> main lamp and small indicator lamp in load module,
description: Visually inspect the main external lamp and the small internal indicator lamp continuously for at least one full 20‑second cycle in a dim environment, confirming whether either lamp’s brightness actually drops or extinguishes in synchrony with the reported ~20 s flicker, or whether both appear steadily lit., outcome='The main external lamp is lit with no observable internal fault during observation.  \nThe internal indicator lamp is also lit with no observable internal fault and is noted to be in parallel with the main load, reflecting the same branch voltage.\nCurrent persistent circuit state [differences with the starting state]:\nNo circuit-level changes introduced by diagnostics.', precise_action_cost=25.0, cost_breakdown=[('observe_component', 10.0), ('open_inspection_panel', 5.0), ('observe_component', 10.0)], simplified_outcome=None), DiagnosticActionResult(action=
name: Test -> timing potentiometer electrical connection to relay driver input,
description: Use a test_continuity (or equivalent) diagnostic to check whether the wiper terminal of the timing potentiometer is actually connected into the relay driver/comparator input node as intended, or instead left floating/only tied to one end. Verify continuity from the pot wiper pad to the corresponding input/feedback node on the driver IC or relay control circuitry, and also verify that the two fixed ends of the potentiometer go to the correct supply and reference nodes., outcome='The control relay continuity is nominal at 0.01 Ω, matching its expected value.  \nContinuity/resistance could not be tested for the Timing Potentiometer and Sensitivity Potentiometer because they have no defined resistance parameter.\nCurrent persistent circuit state [differences with the starting state]:\nNo circuit-level changes introduced by diagnostics.', precise_action_cost=65.0, cost_breakdown=[('open_inspection_panel', 5.0), ('test_continuity', 20.0), ('test_continuity', 20.0), ('test_continuity', 20.0)], simplified_outcome=None), DiagnosticActionResult(action=
name: Test -> control module relay contact path and output connector to load module,
description: Use measure_voltage during the suspected 20 s cycle to monitor the voltage directly across the relay’s switched contacts and across the control‑module output connector to the load (both sides of the contact to reference). Confirm whether any actual interruption or drop in voltage occurs at the relay contacts or at the output pins, despite the coil seeing equal potentials, which would indicate a contact or connector issue versus purely internal driver oscillation., outcome='Measured across the control relay, both terminals are at essentially the same potential (~11.85 V).  \nAt the control‑module output, the (+) cable sits around 11.84–11.85 V while the (−) cable is near 0.03 V, with no polarity inversion indicated between these output cables.\nCurrent persistent circuit state [differences with the starting state]:\nNo circuit-level changes introduced by diagnostics.', precise_action_cost=65.0, cost_breakdown=[('open_inspection_panel', 5.0), ('measure_voltage', 20.0), ('measure_voltage', 20.0), ('measure_voltage', 20.0)], simplified_outcome=None), DiagnosticActionResult(action=
name: Test -> power supply module output and inter‑module connectors,
description: Use measure_voltage and inspect_connections to verify the DC voltage and polarity directly at the power‑supply module’s external output terminals and at each mating connector between modules while the system operates. Confirm that the same stable 12 V and correct polarity seen inside the supply are actually present at the cable terminals and passed cleanly through each connector to the control and load modules, ruling out intermittent/incorrect cabling as the source of the apparent 20 s flicker/instability., outcome='Measured DC voltage remains approximately 11.8–11.9 V on all (+) cables and near 0 V on all (−) cables from the PSU through the control module to the load, with only small drops along the path. All inspected connections show (+) cables mated to (+) ports and (−) cables mated to (−) ports with no POLARITY INVERSION detected.\nCurrent persistent circuit state [differences with the starting state]:\nNo circuit-level changes introduced by diagnostics.', precise_action_cost=280.0, cost_breakdown=[('measure_voltage', 20.0), ('invert_enclosure', 10.0), ('inspect_connections', 10.0), ('inspect_connections', 10.0), ('measure_voltage', 20.0), ('measure_voltage', 20.0), ('open_inspection_panel', 5.0), ('inspect_connections', 10.0), ('inspect_connections', 10.0), ('measure_voltage', 20.0), ('measure_voltage', 20.0), ('inspect_connections', 10.0), ('inspect_connections', 10.0), ('measure_voltage', 20.0), ('measure_voltage', 20.0), ('open_inspection_panel', 5.0), ('inspect_connections', 10.0), ('inspect_connections', 10.0), ('measure_voltage', 20.0), ('measure_voltage', 20.0)], simplified_outcome=None), DiagnosticActionResult(action=
name: Test -> system-level behaviour vs. original symptom description,
description: Use a verify_repair or equivalent system-check operation to explicitly determine whether the lamp is, according to the ground‑truth plant model, still turning off every ~20 s for ~0.5 s as stated in the initial symptom description, or whether the system model now reports the lamp as continuously on. This reconciles the contradiction between the persistent user‑reported flicker and all electrical/visual diagnostics indicating a steady lamp., outcome='The verification step successfully marked the Main Load (lamp) as the hypothesis-verification target.  \nThe simulator reports that the circuit did not converge and is in an unstable or oscillating state, so the ground‑truth model did not return a definitive result about whether the lamp is steady or flickering.\nCurrent persistent circuit state [differences with the starting state]:\nNo circuit-level changes introduced by diagnostics.', precise_action_cost=120.0, cost_breakdown=[('verify_repair', 120.0)], simplified_outcome=None), DiagnosticActionResult(action=
name: Test -> simulation / analysis configuration for relay and lamp (time‑step, tolerances, transient vs. DC operating‑point),
description: Run a diagnostic that switches the circuit analysis from DC operating‑point/steady‑state to a time‑domain transient analysis with appropriate time‑step and relaxed convergence criteria, specifically monitoring the relay driver node and lamp current over several 20 s intervals, to determine whether the reported ‘non‑converging, unstable or oscillating state’ is a numerical artefact of the solver rather than a physical circuit instability., outcome='The requested action could not be mapped to any recognized diagnostic operation. Only actions from the available action list are supported (e.g. measure_voltage, test_continuity, inspect_connections, verify_repair, …).\nCurrent persistent circuit state [differences with the starting state]:\nNo circuit-level changes introduced by diagnostics.', precise_action_cost=0.0, cost_breakdown=[], simplified_outcome=None), DiagnosticActionResult(action=
name: Test -> overall system (logical fault / symptom vs. components),
description: Use a verify_repair (system-level check) with the explicit hypothesis that **no physical component is faulty and the lamp is intended to remain steadily ON in the present ambient light**. Interpret the result only in logical terms (pass/fail of this hypothesis), not as a component repair. This will determine whether the root cause is a non‑component issue such as an incorrect or inconsistent symptom specification versus the actual plant model behaviour., outcome='The system-level verify_repair check did not converge because the circuit is in an unstable or oscillating state.  \nAs a result, the hypothesis that no physical component is faulty and the lamp should remain steadily ON cannot be confirmed or rejected from this test.\nCurrent persistent circuit state [differences with the starting state]:\nNo circuit-level changes introduced by diagnostics.', precise_action_cost=120.0, cost_breakdown=[('verify_repair', 120.0)], simplified_outcome=None), DiagnosticActionResult(action=
name: Test -> ground / reference node integrity across all modules,
description: Use a test_continuity and measure_voltage diagnostic to verify that the 0 V reference node is truly common and correctly tied between the power supply, control, and load modules (including any internal ground symbols or net labels). Check for any unintended extra reference nodes or floating grounds that could cause the simulator to report a globally ‘unstable or oscillating’ state despite all local voltage differences being correct., outcome='All negative cables (PSU, control in/out, and load) show nominal continuity at 0.10 Ω each. The measured voltages indicate small stepwise offsets between these negative cables (0 V to 45.7 mV from PSU Output Cable (−) to Load Input Cable (−)) rather than a single common 0 V reference. No POLARITY INVERSION DETECTED in the provided measurements.\nCurrent persistent circuit state [differences with the starting state]:\nNo circuit-level changes introduced by diagnostics.', precise_action_cost=160.0, cost_breakdown=[('test_continuity', 20.0), ('test_continuity', 20.0), ('test_continuity', 20.0), ('test_continuity', 20.0), ('measure_voltage', 20.0), ('measure_voltage', 20.0), ('measure_voltage', 20.0), ('measure_voltage', 20.0)], simplified_outcome=None), DiagnosticActionResult(action=
name: Test -> global circuit reference / PSU negative terminal vs. other negative nodes,
description: Use measure_voltage to explicitly measure the potential of each negative cable and any internal ground symbols with respect to a single chosen global reference node (e.g., PSU battery negative). Confirm whether multiple distinct 0 V reference nodes exist in the model (small but finite voltage differences between them), which would indicate a missing single global reference definition causing the simulator’s non‑converging ‘unstable’ state., outcome='Each nominally negative cable sits at a slightly different potential, rising from 0.0 V at PSU Output Cable (−) up to 0.0457 V at Load Input Cable (−). These finite voltage differences between the various “(−)” nodes indicate that multiple distinct 0 V reference levels are present in the model instead of a single shared reference.\nCurrent persistent circuit state [differences with the starting state]:\nNo circuit-level changes introduced by diagnostics.', precise_action_cost=80.0, cost_breakdown=[('measure_voltage', 20.0), ('measure_voltage', 20.0), ('measure_voltage', 20.0), ('measure_voltage', 20.0)], simplified_outcome=None), DiagnosticActionResult(action=
name: Test -> PSU Output Cable (−) to Load Input Cable (−) interconnections,
description: Use test_continuity between every pair of nominally negative nodes (PSU negative terminal, PSU Output Cable (−), Control Module Input (−), Control Module Output (−), Load Input (−), and any internal ground symbols) while the circuit is unpowered, to verify whether they are truly hard-wired together (near 0 Ω) or separated by finite resistances/impedances that allow small DC offsets between them., outcome='Continuity tests on the negative cables show nominal resistance of 0.10 Ω for the PSU Output Cable (−), Control Input Cable (−), Control Output Cable (−), and Load Input Cable (−). Continuity testing could not be performed on the Battery, as it has no resistance parameter and the simulation did not converge.\nCurrent persistent circuit state [differences with the starting state]:\nNo circuit-level changes introduced by diagnostics.', precise_action_cost=110.0, cost_breakdown=[('invert_enclosure', 10.0), ('test_continuity', 20.0), ('test_continuity', 20.0), ('test_continuity', 20.0), ('test_continuity', 20.0), ('test_continuity', 20.0)], simplified_outcome=None)] 
